Hopefully you all received my communication on Friday afternoon regarding up to date information for the coming school year! More communication to come this week! Looking forward to seeing my MS Broncos next week!
Dr. McPheron

It is the mission of the Coopersville Area Public Schools to inspire all students to embrace a life-long love of learning, to achieve their goals, and to be compassionate citizens who contribute to the global community.

We are looking to replenish our pool of substitute teachers and substitute paraprofessionals! If you enjoy a job with flexibility, a job where you can make a positive difference in your community, and where you can create your own work schedule, this job is for you!

If you are interested in joining our team, please contact Andrea Kulhawik, Substitute Coordinator, at 616-997-3255 or Akulhawik@capsk12.org.

At CAPS, we are preparing today's students for tomorrow's possibilities!

post_text: Coopersville Career Tech Center Students start at Tech on August 31! Students may choose to attend Tech Center the week of August 24 with their own transportation, however, this is not required. Busing will be provided from Coopersville High School to Tech and back beginning August 31. The AM Tech bus will leave from the High School Athletic Lot at 7:20. The PM Tech bus will leave from the High School Main Lot at 11:12. Students are welcome to drive themselves or carpool to Tech Center.

post_text:
CAPS Families,

Please visit our website and access our Covid-19 resources for the Ottawa County Return to School Toolkit (CAPS Family Edition)
https://coopersvillebroncos.org/downloads/district_files/caps_covid-19_rts_1.pdf

Today's updates and highlights:

1.) Any student/staff that is determined to be in close contact with a person that tests positive for Covid-19 will likely be quarantined for 14 days. Close contact is defined as within 6 feet for more than 15 minutes.

2.) Each district and every building is required to have a Covid-19 liaison that will support all Covid related issues and support the contact tracing process for positive cases.

3.) As required by Executive Order 2020 - 164, face coverings will be required all PreK - 12 students and staff.

Thank you,
Matt Spencer
Superintendent

post_text:
Voters on August 4 will be asked to consider the approval of the 18-mill non-homestead property tax levy for a period of two years. Schools across Michigan have levied this tax since 1994 as a part of their per pupil funding system.

In an effort to help voters understand the ballot question, we compiled information regarding FAQs and shared them in an email to all families, today. The email explains how the tax impacts school funding, the definition of a non-homestead property, and it gives history of this proposal.

To review the ballot language, or find more information about Coopersville School's current financial condition, please visit our website at www.coopersvillebroncos.org

Hey there middle school students!

I hope you are doing well, staying safe and healthy, and finding some time to enjoy all the great things of summer!

During the course of your day, schedule 30-60 minutes to read, participate in the summer learning plan, or simply research an area of interest!

Fun Facts:
A hummingbird‚Äôs heart can beat up to 1,260 times per minute (in one species, at least). -- Science fact

The Pacific Ocean is larger than all land masses on Earth combined. -- Social Studies fact

The term ‚ÄúOK‚Äù probably comes from a misspelling of the phrase ‚Äúall correct.‚Äù -- ELA fact

The average lifespan of an MLB baseball is just 7 pitches. -- Math fact (that is a lot of baseballs per game!) ‚öæÔ∏è‚öæÔ∏è

üì£ You are missed! I look forward to seeing your smiles and hearing about your adventures!

Dr. McPheron

post_text:
Three important items from Coopersville Middle School:

üì£ Buy a padlock with a combination!
Although the numbers will change for your student's locker combination, the muscle memory and practice will help immensely!

üì£Take about 30-60 minutes a day to exercise the brain!
Read 20 minutes each day!
Practice addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division math facts!
Utilize some websites from the summer learning plan!

üì£Stay connected!
I send Blackboard Connect messages almost every Friday during the school year, sometimes I also make a phone call!
If you did not receive this Blackboard Connect message today, make sure that your email is updated with your building office!
I will begin weekly communication beginning in August!
Looking forward to partnering with you over the next few years! I hope you have a fantastic summer.....full of many wonderful memories!

Dr. Tricia McPheron

We will be available to distribute student materials this week Wednesday, May 6th from 3:00 p.m. - 6:00 p.m. Hopefully this additional evening time period will help you! This is for ALL 6th-8th grade students! Again, this includes: personal items from lockers, gym lockers, medicine, some posted artwork, instruments, etc.

Drop off materials/packet work:

For those families interested in dropping off printed, completed assignments or library books, the MS main entrance vestibule will be open from 9:00 a.m. - 11:00 a.m. on Wednesdays and Thursdays for the next 5 weeks for drop off.

There will be a box in the main entrance vestibule to place completed work or library books.

Students should include their name and the specific teacher‚Äôs name on each completed assignment sheet.

Thank you!

post_text:
Congratulations to our very own Luke Cunningham for recently being honored with the Daughters of American Revolution (DAR) Good Citizen Award and Scholarship Contest, pictured here with other local winners.

The DAR Good Citizens Award and Scholarship Contest is intended to encourage and reward the qualities of good citizenship. The program is open to all high school seniors. The award recognizes and rewards
individuals who possess the qualities of dependability, service, leadership, and patriotism in their homes, schools and communities.

These students are selected by their teachers and peers because they demonstrate these qualities to an outstanding degree. Chapter winners are entered into the state contest, and state winners are entered into the national contest.

Way to go, Luke!

Be a TTQ coach!

YOU can make a difference in the life of a 3rd-5th grade boy!
YOU can help instill a life-long love of running AND model healthy choices and interactions. Coaches can be men or women; we are looking for a positive attitude and a passion for helping kids reach their full potential. You do not need to be an experienced runner! High School juniors/seniors can be assistant coaches, too!

For more information, please contact Brandon Melnyk at bmelnyk@arborcircle.org or Sara Lothschutz at slothschutz@capsk12.org.

On this National Inventors' Day, we would like to üì£ spotlight the CAPS Science Clubs. Last evening, students in the Robotics Club gave a presentation to the CAPS School Board about the Robotics Program.

Under the guidance of CHS teacher Ryan Schoenborn, CAPS Science Clubs work on many activities such as dissections, FIRST Robotics, FIRST Lego League, Underwater Vehicle, Circuits and many more.

"An Inventor fails 999 times, and if he succeeds once, he's in. He treats his failures simply as practice shots". - Charles F. Kettering

ATTENTION SENIORS!

Senior pictures are due no later than March 1st! Please email a vertical photo as well as a quote to: yearbook@capsk12.org.

üö´‚ö†Ô∏èPlease remember, it is illegal to take photos on railroad tracks. If your photo is on a railroad track, it will not go in the yearbook. Photos also need to be sent in as vertical shots. We cannot crop horizontal photos to make them vertical. Also, we can use full body photos however, the person will look really small! We recommend using photos that are from the waist (or shoulders!) up.

If you have any further questions, please email yearbook@capsk12.org!
